krijk"},"en":{"about 1438–":"about 1438–Deceased","1434–Male":"1434–Deceased","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1462–Male":"1462–Deceased","1464–Male":"1464–Deceased","1466–Male":"1466–Deceased","1468–Female":"1468–Deceased","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","1472–Female":"1472–Deceased","1474–Female":"1474–Deceased","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","abt. 1466":"about 1466","abt. 1468":"about 1468","abt. 1474":"about 1474","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","abt. 1464":"about 1464","1470":"1470","abt 1462":"about 1462","abt. 1470":"about 1470","abt. 1472":"about 1472","abt. 1460":"about 1460","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","about 1438":"about 1438","1464":"1464","1474":"1474","1438":"1438","of Altgwawddu, Glam., Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","of Altgwawrddu, Glam., Wales.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Koch   and, in North America, probably also an altered form of this.","Catalan: occupational name from <i>coc(h)</i> ‘cook’.","Polish: unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Koch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Otto, Erwin, Klaus, Helmut, Fritz, Heinz, Gerhard, Wolfgang, Ernst, Florian.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name from Middle High German <i>koch</i>, German <i>Koch</i> ‘cook’. The name in this sense is also established in some other European countries, e.g. in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and Denmark.","Czech and Slovak: from <i>Koch</i>, a pet form of   Kochan   or of any other personal name beginning with <i>Ko-</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Lewis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Lewis</i>, <i>Leweis</i>, <i>Lowis</i>, from ancient Germanic (originally West Frankish) <i>Hludwig</i> (itself from <i>hlōd-</i> ‘fame, famous’ + <i>wīg-</i> ‘battle’). This was Latinized as <i>Ludovicus</i> and <i>Chlodovisus</i>, which were gallicized as <i>Clovis</i> or <i>Clouis</i>, French <i>Louis</i>. The name may also appear as <i>Lawis</i>, <i>Laweys</i>, <i>Lawes</i>, by unrounding of the vowel of <i>Lowis</i> on the analogy of the variation between <i>Low</i> and <i>Law</i> as pet forms of Middle English <i>Lourence</i> alias <i>Laurence</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Laws   2 and compare   Lawrence  .","Welsh: adopted for the Welsh personal name <i>Llywelyn</i> (see   Llewellyn  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’. This is one of the most common Old Irish personal names. It is derived from <i>Lugh</i> ‘brightness’, which was the name of a Celtic god."],"variants":[{"name":"Laws","meanings":["English: variant of   Law   (pet form of   Lawrence  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish or Irish   McLeish  . Compare   McLaws  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"McGlew","meanings":["Irish: most probably from <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’, a Gaelic personal name (referencing the god Lugh), sometimes Anglicized as   Lewis  . However, both Woulfe and MacLysaght consider <i>McGlew</i> to be a shortened form of <b>Mac Dhuinnshléibhe</b> (see   McAleavey   and   Dunleavy  )."]},{"name":"Lowis","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewis   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Coch Ap Lewis was born about 1438, in Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 4 sons and 4 daughters with Richard Ap Lewis."},"et":{"about 1438–":"umbes 1438–Surnud","1434–Male":"1434–Surnud","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1462–Male":"1462–Surnud","1464–Male":"1464–Surnud","1466–Male":"1466–Surnud","1468–Female":"1468–Surnud","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","1472–Female":"1472–Surnud","1474–Female":"1474–Surnud","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","abt. 1466":"umbes 1466","abt. 1468":"umbes 1468","abt. 1474":"umbes 1474","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","abt. 1464":"umbes 1464","1470":"1470","abt 1462":"umbes 1462","abt. 1470":"umbes 1470","abt. 1472":"umbes 1472","abt. 1460":"umbes 1460","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","about 1438":"umbes 1438","1464":"1464","1474":"1474","1438":"1438","of Altgwawddu, Glam., Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","of Altgwawrddu, Glam., Wales.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1438–":"noin 1438–Kuollut","1434–Male":"1434–Kuollut","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1462–Male":"1462–Kuollut","1464–Male":"1464–Kuollut","1466–Male":"1466–Kuollut","1468–Female":"1468–Kuollut","1470–Female":"1470–Kuollut","1472–Female":"1472–Kuollut","1474–Female":"1474–Kuollut","1438–Female":"1438–Kuollut","abt. 1466":"noin 1466","abt. 1468":"noin 1468","abt. 1474":"noin 1474","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","abt. 1464":"noin 1464","1470":"1470","abt 1462":"noin 1462","abt. 1470":"noin 1470","abt. 1472":"noin 1472","abt. 1460":"noin 1460","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","about 1438":"noi